#!/usr/bin/env ssc
---
name: v2-option-exists
description: Option.exists is unimplemented on v2 — None.exists raises an unhandled Op, Some.exists returns a Stub instead of a Boolean
backends: [int]
---

# v2: `Option.exists` is entirely missing

Found driving busi's live hub auth on `--v2` (`hasRole`/`isOwner`:
`identity.exists(i => i.roles.contains(role))` on an `Option[Identity]`) —
this is a fundamental, pervasive gap: `Option.exists` isn't dispatched at
all, for EITHER arm.

- `None.exists(pred)` → unhandled `Op("None.exists", <closure>, <closure>)`
  surfaces to the top instead of returning `false`.
- `Some.exists(pred)` → `Stub("Some.exists")` instead of evaluating `pred`
  and returning a `Boolean`.

v1 is correct on both (`false` / `true`). This blocks essentially any
auth/role check written the idiomatic way
(`identity.exists(predicate)` instead of a manual
`match { case Some(x) => pred(x); case None => false }`), which is common
throughout busi's domain code — not specific to money-loop or HTTP.

Found 2026-07-09 by busi (fable) while driving a live v2 hub through the
full JDG money-loop simulator cycle — every auth-gated route
(`isPaired`/`isOwner`/operator checks) crashes or misbehaves the moment it
reaches a role check on a `None` or `Some` identity.

```scalascript
val n: Option[Int] = None
println(n.exists(x => x > 0))
val s: Option[Int] = Some(5)
println(s.exists(x => x > 0))
```
